The King Paradox

In the Wednesday staff meeting, Thompson acknowledged that it was all well =
and good to cover Trump=E2=80=99s cabinet appointments, but he did not want=
 CNN to go wall-to-wall on the daily Trump drama for the next four years, a=
s the network mostly had under Zucker during the president-elect=E2=80=99s =
first administration. There were a lot of other stories out in the U.S. and=
 around the world, Thompson said, and it was clear that audiences were sick=
 of the way the media covers politics.

Thompson pointed to two examples that helped articulate a path forward: Joh=
n King=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CAll Over the Map=E2=80=9D series, an election-sea=
son voter-interview feature from the battleground states=E2=80=94effectivel=
y a =E2=80=9Cman on the street=E2=80=9D subgenre, only with better producti=
on values and often =E2=80=9Cin the home=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94and Donie O=E2=80=
=99Sullivan=E2=80=99s slickly produced
packages from the front lines of MAGA America featuring, as Thompson put it=
, the =E2=80=9Cpeople we don=E2=80=99t normally hear on CNN.=E2=80=9D (Thom=
pson singled out an interview in which a January 6 rioter expressed confide=
nce that he=E2=80=99d be pardoned by Trump.) In other words, more reporting=
 from the field, less pontificating from the studio.

To many, Thompson=E2=80=99s remarks were welcome and long overdue. Much of =
CNN=E2=80=99s pre-election coverage=E2=80=94as well as MSNBC=E2=80=99s=E2=
=80=94featured roundtables overpopulated with familiar, mostly anti-Trump g=
reenroom analysts expressing the customary outrage and incredulity, which n=
ever equalled a winning programming strategy. And his perspective was very =
welcome to the journalists and correspondents on nonpolitical beats, many o=
f whom have felt marginalized or underappreciated for more than a decade=E2=
=80=94ever since Zucker first implemented his =E2=80=9Cone big story,=E2=80=
=9D wall-to-wall strategy, which eventually just meant =E2=80=9Call in on T=
rump.=E2=80=9D

For
others, however, Thompson=E2=80=99s prescription stoked latent fears about =
his editorial leadership, which are distinct from the usual anxieties about=
 the viability of his business transformation. =E2=80=9CMan on the street=
=E2=80=9D is hardly a programming innovation, these folks noted, and MAGA-w=
orld anthropology=E2=80=94Let=E2=80=99s all marvel at these election denier=
s in the wild!=E2=80=94was the exact playbook that television and digital n=
ews sites tried to run in the aftermath of Trump=E2=80=99s first victory. O=
=E2=80=99Sullivan and his colleague Elle Reeve have been doing that sort of=
 reporting for six years. Did Thompson really like this stuff=E2=80=94or wa=
s he just sick of everything else?

Under Thompson, CNN=E2=80=99s fate is often framed=E2=80=94yes, very often =
by me=E2=80=94as a linear-vs.-digital dialectic, a question of whether or n=
ot The Man From The New York Times can transform the 44-year-old cable netw=
ork into a multiplatform, subscription-supported service that will maintain=
 CNN=E2=80=99s
global influence in a post-linear world. Increasingly, many of Thompson=E2=
=80=99s critics at CNN argue that this misses the point. In their view, it=
=E2=80=99s not simply a question of whether he=E2=80=99s prioritizing digit=
al over television. Even the digital folks are quick to point out that he h=
as yet to implement any big digital innovations, let alone overhaul the mes=
sy and chaotic aughts-era homepage.

The true problem, these people say, is that Thompson appears to be ignoring=
 the content itself. In their view, it doesn=E2=80=99t matter what brillian=
t digital delivery system he devises if what=E2=80=99s being conveyed in th=
e pipes is not relevant or engaging. And, indeed, he has yet to publicly ar=
ticulate an identity for the new CNN beyond pointing out the obvious: Linea=
r is dying.

Alas, these sorts of unhappy-family squabbles acknowledge the sad and incre=
asingly clear truth of it all=E2=80=94this is a worsening situation without=
 a whole lot of good solutions. And the timing of
Thompson=E2=80=99s remarks, so proximate to the forthcoming layoffs, intima=
tes that his plan may actually be deceptively simple: drastically cut costs=
, pivot to the center to defend the cable network=E2=80=99s value among dis=
tributors, and pull it all off with more credibility than Chris Licht. If t=
he digital sub thing works, that=E2=80=99d be swell, too.

And yet, there=E2=80=99s likely another unspoken element to all this. For g=
enerations, news networks earned their margins by filtering their newsgathe=
ring infrastructure through the prism of a well-coiffed anchor who personal=
ized the information by looking directly into the camera. Our politics have=
 changed, our monoculture has collapsed, and our media economy=E2=80=94fair=
ly or not=E2=80=94values authenticity most of all. It=E2=80=99s unclear how=
 CNN=E2=80=99s current product fits into this dynamic, and the network=E2=
=80=99s rank and file sure haven=E2=80=99t heard Thompson=E2=80=99s point o=
f view on the subject, either, besides his pat references to battleground c=
ontent
and red state diaries. Indeed, all of this reinforces a straightforward, if=
 depressing message: The problem isn=E2=80=99t just that Thompson is no sav=
ior; the real heartbreaker is that no one is.

