          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In the Wednesday st=
aff meeting, Thompson acknowledged that it was all well and good to cover T=
rump=E2=80=99s cabinet appointments, but he did <i>not</i> want CNN to go w=
all-to-wall on the daily Trump drama for the next four years, as the networ=
k mostly had under Zucker during the president-elect=E2=80=99s first admini=
stration. There were a lot of <i>other</i> stories out in the U.S. and arou=
nd the world, Thompson said, and it was clear that audiences were sick of t=
he way the media covers politics.<br/><br/>Thompson pointed to two examples=
 that helped articulate a path forward: <b>John King</b>=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9CAll Over the Map=E2=80=9D series, an election-season voter-interview fea=
ture from the battleground states=E2=80=94effectively a =E2=80=9Cman on the=
 street=E2=80=9D subgenre, only with better production values and often =E2=
=80=9Cin the home=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94and <b>Donie O=E2=80=99Sullivan</b>=E2=
=80=99s slickly produced
packages from the front lines of MAGA America featuring, as Thompson put it=
, the =E2=80=9Cpeople we don=E2=80=99t normally hear on CNN.=E2=80=9D (Thom=
pson singled out an interview in which a January 6 rioter expressed confide=
nce that he=E2=80=99d be pardoned by Trump.) In other words, more reporting=
 from the field, less pontificating from the studio. <br/><br/>To many, Tho=
mpson=E2=80=99s remarks were welcome and long overdue. Much of CNN=E2=80=99=
s pre-election coverage=E2=80=94as well as MSNBC=E2=80=99s=E2=80=94featured=
 roundtables overpopulated with familiar, mostly anti-Trump greenroom analy=
sts expressing the customary outrage and incredulity, which never equalled =
a winning programming strategy. And his perspective was <i>very </i>welcome=
 to the journalists and correspondents on nonpolitical beats, many of whom =
have felt marginalized or underappreciated for more than a decade=E2=80=94e=
ver since Zucker first implemented his =E2=80=9Cone big story,=E2=80=9D wal=
l-to-wall strategy, which eventually just meant =E2=80=9Call in on Trump.=
=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>For
others, however, Thompson=E2=80=99s prescription stoked latent fears about =
his editorial leadership, which are distinct from the usual anxieties about=
 the viability of his business transformation. =E2=80=9CMan on the street=
=E2=80=9D is hardly a programming innovation, these folks noted, and MAGA-w=
orld anthropology=E2=80=94<i>Let=E2=80=99s all marvel at these election den=
iers in the wild!</i>=E2=80=94was the exact playbook that television and di=
gital news sites tried to run in the aftermath of Trump=E2=80=99s first vic=
tory. O=E2=80=99Sullivan and his colleague <b>Elle Reeve</b> have been doin=
g that sort of reporting for six years. Did Thompson <i>really</i> like thi=
s stuff=E2=80=94or was he just sick of everything else?<br/><br/>Under Thom=
pson, CNN=E2=80=99s fate is often framed=E2=80=94yes, very often by <i>me</=
i>=E2=80=94as a linear-vs.-digital dialectic, a question of whether or not =
<i>The Man From The New York Times</i> can transform the 44-year-old cable =
network into a multiplatform, subscription-supported service that will main=
tain CNN=E2=80=99s
global influence in a post-linear world. Increasingly, many of Thompson=E2=
=80=99s critics at CNN argue that this misses the point. In their view, it=
=E2=80=99s not simply a question of whether he=E2=80=99s prioritizing digit=
al over television. Even the digital folks are quick to point out that he h=
as yet to implement any big digital innovations, let alone overhaul the mes=
sy and chaotic aughts-era homepage. <br/><br/>The true problem, these peopl=
e say, is that Thompson appears to be ignoring the content itself. In their=
 view, it doesn=E2=80=99t matter what brilliant digital delivery system he =
devises if what=E2=80=99s being conveyed in the pipes is not relevant or en=
gaging. And, indeed, he has yet to publicly articulate an identity for the =
new CNN <i>beyond </i>pointing out the obvious: Linear is dying. <br/><br/>=
Alas, these sorts of unhappy-family squabbles acknowledge the sad and incre=
asingly clear truth of it all=E2=80=94this is a worsening situation without=
 a whole lot of good solutions. And the timing of
Thompson=E2=80=99s remarks, so proximate to the forthcoming layoffs, intima=
tes that his plan may actually be deceptively simple: drastically cut costs=
, pivot to the center to defend the cable network=E2=80=99s value among dis=
tributors, and pull it all off with more credibility than <b>Chris Licht</b=
>. If the digital sub thing works, that=E2=80=99d be swell, too.<br/><br/>A=
nd yet, there=E2=80=99s likely another unspoken element to all this. For ge=
nerations, news networks earned their margins by filtering their newsgather=
ing infrastructure through the prism of a well-coiffed anchor who personali=
zed the information by looking directly into the camera. Our politics have =
changed, our monoculture has collapsed, and our media economy=E2=80=94fairl=
y or not=E2=80=94values authenticity most of all. It=E2=80=99s unclear how =
CNN=E2=80=99s current product fits into this dynamic, and the network=E2=80=
=99s rank and file sure haven=E2=80=99t heard Thompson=E2=80=99s point of v=
iew on the subject, either, besides his pat references to battleground cont=
ent
and red state diaries. Indeed, all of this reinforces a straightforward, if=
 depressing message: The problem isn=E2=80=99t just that Thompson is no sav=
ior; the real heartbreaker is that no one is.<br/></td>
         </tr>
